Dear Mayor Mcneill,
I write to you in order to summarize our team’s economic analysis regarding the effectiveness
of CPI Indexing Plans versus the current negotiation method for the annual salary adjustments
of the firemen in the town of Noronto.
We have concluded that the most effective course of action would be to switch from the current
negotiation method to a CPI Index plan. Our estimate suggests the town could be saving
roughly $10,000 each year by doing so. This being so under the assumption that inflation
increases steadily in the near future, and that the firemen have conventional consumer
preferences. Attached to this letter is our complete analysis, which I invite you to peruse in
hopes that it will aid your decision-making process, and provide justification for our
conclusions and findings.
Please let us know if there are any clarifications that we may assist you with.

Economics Analysis of CPI Indexing versus Negotiation for
Salary Adjustment of Noronto Firemen
The town of Noronto has 10 firemen with each currently being paid $65,000 as an annual salary.
This report aims to analyze whether adopting a Consumer Price Index (CPI) salary indexing
plan is more economically advantageous than the current method of salary negotiation which
costs $10,000 and whether the town of Noronto should switch adjustment methods.
In this report, food (f) and shelter (s) are the two goods analyzed in terms of optimum
consumption bundles given by the firemen’s preferences and budget constraints. Noronto is
modelled as a small town in Ontario, so average consumer data values henceforth are from
Ontario. The average expenditure on food from stores and shelter in 2019 was $6,150, and
$21,519 respectively
1
. These are used as the prices of food and shelter in the analysis model.
Preferences of the individual in question are what truly determine the effectiveness of using
CPI indexing plans. Preferences are difficult to measure in real life, but the scope of this report
covers what would be effective for two different common preference models, specifically with
Cobb-Douglas, and perfect complements.

Effects of a Price Change
In this analysis, projected price inflation for 2020 is estimated using price inflation from 2018
to 2019. This was quoted as a 3.6% and 2.3% increase by Statistics Canada for food and shelter
respectively.
3
This shifts food and shelter prices from $6,150 and $21,519 to $6,371 and
$22,014, respectively. With the same level of income, the new budget constraint for the firemen
would be:

With these new prices from inflation the firemen can no longer afford their original optimum
bundle given their current salaries and their preferences. At this point there are two ways of
adjusting their salary so that they can at least afford their optimum bundle; either by hiring a
negotiator to moderate an ideal salary for the firemen and their government employers, or
adjusting it by the CPI index.
Negotiating a New Salary
Hiring a negotiator results in a new salary such that the budget constraint has the same slope
as the price change budget constraint (Equation 3), but is now tangent to the firemen’s utility
function. This new salary is calculated to be $66,816 with new optimum bundle to be 5.27 units
of food and 1.51 units of shelter.

This method of adjustment allows the firemen to consume a bundle that gives them the exact
same utility as before, but it comes at the cost of the negotiator at $10,000 per year in addition
to the change in salary.
CPI Indexing to Adjust Salary
The original salary $65,000 is increased by the same percentage change as food and shelter; so
$65,000 becomes $66,915

The CPI Indexing has overestimated the salary that would have made the fireman as well off
as before as we can see from the graphs. This is clearest from the close up of the graph
intercepts. In this model it can be calculated how much the overestimate would cost annually
compared to the cost of hiring a negotiator.
Comparing Cost of CPI Overestimate and Cost of Negotiator & Conclusions
The additional costs on top of the original salaries for the firemen are estimated to be $19,150
for the CPI overestimate and $28,160 for the negotiator
6
, given the assumptions we made in
the analysis. This would suggest that the more economical option would be to go with a CPI
index, especially when considering the extra time and planning it takes to host the negotiation
in addition to the firemen getting paid more than they would have bargained for. However,
many assumptions were made in this analysis which may not hold true in the real world, which
leads to a degree of uncertainty in the conclusions drawn. It could be argued that assuming a
steady inflation rate of prices for the next few years (varying only by a one or two percent),
and general Cobb-Douglas preferences, it is likely that the values calculated will end up being
similar to the ones in this analysis as these are probably the biggest assumptions made.

A Note on Perfect Complements
It is also relevant to note that with perfect complement preferences, income is always perfectly
adjusted with the CPI index leaving the individual consuming their exact original optimum
bundle (see Graph 5, 6, 7). It is however unlikely that all the firemen have perfect complement
preferences as this tends to be quite uncommon for all goods.
